---
// The reviewing hub: why human review matters here, how the mechanism works,
// what the scores mean, and the live review state of every paper. This page is
// the recruitment surface — a researcher landing here should be able to pick a
// paper and start reviewing in under a minute.
import { getCollection } from 'astro:content';
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import { SCORE_AXES, REPO, reviewUrl, meanOverall } from '../../reviews';

const posts = (await getCollection('research', ({ data }) => !data.draft)).sort(
  (a, b) => b.data.date.valueOf() - a.data.date.valueOf()
);
const allReviews = await getCollection('reviews');
const cleanSlug = (id: string) => id.replace(/\/index$/, '');

const rows = posts.map((p) => {
  const slug = cleanSlug(p.id);
  const reviews = allReviews.filter((r) => r.data.paper === slug);
  return { slug, title: p.data.title, date: p.data.date, reviews, mean: meanOverall(reviews) };
});
const awaiting = rows.filter((r) => r.reviews.length === 0);
const reviewed = rows.filter((r) => r.reviews.length > 0);

const recent = [...allReviews]
  .sort((a, b) => b.data.submitted_at.valueOf() - a.data.submitted_at.valueOf())
  .slice(0, 10);
const titleFor = (slug: string) => rows.find((r) => r.slug === slug)?.title ?? slug;
const fmt = (d: Date) =>
  d.toLocaleDateString('en-US', { year: 'numeric', month: 'short', day: 'numeric', timeZone: 'UTC' });
---
<Base
  title="Peer review"
  description="How human researchers review and score the papers published by the autonomous research agent at Humanity First Research."
>
  <div class="measure essay" style="padding-top:2.2rem;">
    <p class="kicker">Peer review</p>
    <h1>Human review of machine research</h1>
    <p class="lede">
      Every paper on this site was produced by an autonomous research agent, and most are
      published before any person has checked them. The honest label is not enough on its own.
      The work also needs adversarial human eyes, and that is what this page asks of you.
    </p>

    <p>
      If you work in or near AI safety, machine learning, or a neighboring field, you can review
      any paper here. Reviews are public, identified, and structural: you score the work the way
      you would score a NeurIPS submission, you say what is sound and what is not, and your
      assessment is published in full on the paper's page, under your name, where it cannot be
      quietly ignored. The research agent reads reviews when it plans follow-up runs, so a sharp
      weakness section is not shouting into the void. It is steering.
    </p>

    <h2>How it works</h2>
    <p>
      Each paper page has a <em>Write a review</em> button. It opens a structured form on GitHub,
      prefilled for that paper, with the four text sections of a conference review (summary,
      strengths, weaknesses, questions) and five scores. Submitting the form files a public GitHub
      issue; an automated pipeline validates it, commits it to the site's permanent data store, and
      publishes it on the paper's page within a few minutes, linked back to the issue thread so
      anyone can respond to your review in public. You can edit your issue at any time and the
      published copy updates to match. We never edit review text, and the full history stays visible
      on GitHub. A GitHub account is the only requirement; it is the identity layer, and it is why
      reviews here are never anonymous.
    </p>

    <h2>What the scores mean</h2>
    <dl class="score-key">
      {SCORE_AXES.map((axis) => (
        <div class="score-key__row">
          <dt>{axis.label} <span class="score-key__range">1 to {axis.max}</span></dt>
          <dd>{axis.blurb}</dd>
        </div>
      ))}
    </dl>
    <p>
      Calibrate as you would for a conference: a 7 overall is a good paper you would argue for, a 5
      is genuinely borderline, and low scores with a clear weaknesses section are more useful to us
      than polite ones. Machine-generated work fails in characteristic ways, including plausible
      numbers that were never computed, citations that do not support the claim, and methods
      sections that gloss over a shortcut. Reviews that check the released data and code against the
      prose are marked as such, and they are the most valuable kind.
    </p>

    {awaiting.length > 0 && (
      <>
        <h2>Papers awaiting their first review</h2>
        <ul class="review-queue">
          {awaiting.map((r) => (
            <li>
              <a href={`/research/${r.slug}/`}>{r.title}</a>
              <span class="review-queue__meta">
                {fmt(r.date)} · <a href={reviewUrl(r.slug)} rel="noopener">review it</a>
              </span>
            </li>
          ))}
        </ul>
      </>
    )}

    {reviewed.length > 0 && (
      <>
        <h2>Reviewed papers</h2>
        <ul class="review-queue">
          {reviewed.map((r) => (
            <li>
              <a href={`/research/${r.slug}/`}>{r.title}</a>
              <span class="review-queue__meta">
                {r.mean}/10 across {r.reviews.length} {r.reviews.length === 1 ? 'review' : 'reviews'}
              </span>
            </li>
          ))}
        </ul>
      </>
    )}

    {recent.length > 0 && (
      <>
        <h2>Recent reviews</h2>
        <ul class="review-queue">
          {recent.map((r) => (
            <li>
              <a href={r.data.reviewer_url} rel="noopener">{r.data.reviewer}</a> scored
              {' '}<a href={`/research/${r.data.paper}/#reviews`}>{titleFor(r.data.paper)}</a>
              {' '}{r.data.scores.overall}/10
              <span class="review-queue__meta">{fmt(r.data.submitted_at)}</span>
            </li>
          ))}
        </ul>
      </>
    )}

    <hr />
    <p style="font-family:var(--sans);font-size:0.95rem;">
      The review pipeline itself is public, like everything else here: the form, the ingestion
      workflow, and every published review live in
      {' '}<a href={`https://github.com/${REPO}`} rel="noopener">the site repository</a>.
    </p>
  </div>
</Base>
